<!--
/SLIDES/01: No CSS here to illustrate importance of good markup
- when css, javascript are disabled, the site should maintain some structure and legibility
- practice good semantics
- imagine your users are actually reading the html markup
- would they be able to make sense of the content?
-->
<% if (slide >= 1) { %>

<% } %>

<!--
/SLIDES/02: Restore baseline CSS and introduce <meta name='viewport'>
- Device Pixel vs CSS Pixel, layout viewport (document) vs visual viewport (device)
- width=device-width sets layout viewport to specific width (device-width = no horizontal scrolling)
- initial-scale=1 sets zoom to fit neatly into the display
- user-scalable=no
- css @viewport ? broswser support unpredictable
- without this meta tag, all other "mobile friendly" efforts are in vain
-->
<% if (slide >= 2) { %>
  <% include ./css_baseline %>
  <meta name='viewport' content='width=device-width,initial-scale=1,user-scalable=no'>
<% } %>

<!--
/SLIDES/03: Images and embedded videos don't automatically resize like other block elements.
-->
<% if (slide >= 3) { %>
  <link href='/css/media.css' rel='stylesheet' type='text/css' />
<% } %>

<!--
/SLIDES/04: CSS media queries help adjust layouts as display size increases.
- this is where the "mobile first" concept comes into play
- usually querying display width
- as a strategy, default to styles that work well on small screens
- using "min-width" introduce new styles for larger displays
- be consistent, use the same trigger points, don't suddenly switch to "max-width"
-->
<% if (slide >= 4) { %>
  <link href='/css/layouts.css' rel='stylesheet' type='text/css' />
<% } %>

<!--
/SLIDES/05: Design patterns to the rescue.
- Tiling content helps keep units of content more scanable
-->
<% if (slide >= 5) { %>
  <link href='/css/feature_tiles.css' rel='stylesheet' type='text/css' />
<% } %>

<!--
/SLIDES/06: Get that content max width under control
-->
<% if (slide >= 6) { %>
  <link href='/css/max_width.css' rel='stylesheet' type='text/css' />
<% } %>

<!--
/SLIDES/07: Re-arranging header on larger screens.
- again, due to our "mobile first" strategy, we don't have to overwrite much css to modify the layout
-->
<% if (slide >= 7) { %>
  <link href='/css/header_wide.css' rel='stylesheet' type='text/css' />
<% } %>
